			<h4>What is the treatment like?</h4>
			<p>
				Administered by a licensed nurse or physician, a small hand-held laser device is used to dispense the light beams that are glided through the treatment area. You might experience a slight discomfort during the session, akin to the sensation of a rubber band snapping against your skin. If required, a topical anesthetic can be applied 60 minutes before your session. Some people like to briefly apply an ice pack afterwards. During the procedure you'll be required to wear tinted goggles to protect your eyes from the laser light.Laser hair removal uses various wavelengths of light to destroy hair follice and each system is different.
			</p>

			<p>
				For each treatment, we typically schedule five to six sessions about four to five weeks apart.
			</p>
			<hr />

			<h4>Am I a good candidate?</h4>
			<p>
				Laser hair removal works when the light beams are absorbed by the melanin in the hair shaft and follicle. People with dark hair are considered the best candidates. Blonde, gray, and strawberry-blonde hair may not absorb the laser light. And contrast between the hair and your skin is also important, so people with dark or olive-coloured skin may not have enough contrast for the beams to be absorbed by the hair follicle.
			</p>
			<p>
				Each person responds differently to laser hair removal. Some may require more treatments than others. And sometimes laser hair removal can't eliminate hair completely. If some hair does grow back, it's usually thinner and finer than before the treatment.
			</p>

			<p>
				Our practioners, who are extremely experienced at performing Laser Hair Removal procedures, begin with a melanin test on the area before each treatment to ensure the area is safe to treat. If the melanin in the skin is found to be too high the treatment will be postponed until it is at an accepted limit
			</p>

			<hr />
			<h4>What can I expect before and after treatment?</h4>
			<p>
				<strong>Before Your Treatment</strong>
				<br />
				Laser hair removal kills only the actively growing hairs and hair follicles. For this reason, other hair removal techniques should be stopped at least six weeks before laser treatment. You can still shave and, in fact, you'll be asked to shave your treatment area 24 to 48 hours before your scheduled appointment. Because laser hair removal depends on the colour of your skin and hair, you should not sun tan for a minimum of six weeks before your treatment.
			</p>

			<p>
				<strong>After Your Treatment</strong>
				<br />
				There may be some redness or bumps immediately after the treatment, but nothing that will keep you from your daily activities. Some people apply a temporary icepack on their treatment area. You don't need time to recover after your session, so you can participate in almost all of your regular activities immediately after your appointment. You should, however, avoid exposure to the sun for the following four to six weeks. The initial treatment may kill between 20 to 40 % of the hair. After four treatments, you can expect 80 % hairs destroyed. Few subsequent treatments will give you freed from more than 90 % of hair.
			</p>

			<hr />
			<h4>What should I look for in a laser practitioner?</h4>
			<p>
				The treatment should be performed by a registered nurse (RNs) or physician who's trained to operate a laser. Different treatment choices must be made for each patient. Side effects, such as skin discoloration, can result if the laser is operated by an inexperienced practitioner. We, at Dr Kiran's Dermatology, provide only laser trained RNs or physicians to deliver high-quality care to our patients.
			</p>
			<hr />
			<h4>Are there any risks?</h4>
			<p>
				Laser hair removal is a reasonably safe procedure, Some people may experience redness, swelling, bruising, blistering, or superficial skin erosions that are temporary and heal
				with time.
			</p>
			<hr />
			<h4>When will I see the results?</h4>
			<p>
				Usually results are visible after your first treatment. However long lasting may be noticeable only after achieving six to eight treatments.
			</p>
			<hr />
			<h4>How many treatments will I need? </h4>
			<p>
				The number of treatments required will depend on the area being treated and also the skin colour, hair colour, texture and density. Secondly, patient's response to treatment is also a deciding factor.
			</p>

